 to Hurry G.\nTruman, President cf the United\nStates. 1 am taking this opportunity\nto make it public because ii deals\nwith c problem vita! to the interests\nof the auto workers.\nDEAR MR. PRESIDENT:\nv our announcement on the night\ncl Tuesday, August 14, that ;bc Em\npire cf japan had surrendered to the\narmed a/ th\u00b0 United Nations\nbrought joy ic the hearts o{ the\nAmencan people\nWithin 43 houis of your announce\nment of final victory, however, then\nfeeling of joy had given way to un\ncertainty insecurity, and leaf cf the\nfuture; for within tvro days, mere\nthan 200,0CQ people in the city of\nDetroit and nearly five million work\ners throughout the country were\nthrown onto trie sireets as a new\narmy cf the unemployed.\nNOT EXPENDABLE\nThese workers. Mr. President\nare not expendable. During the\nhour of our nation's greatest\ncrisis, they gave unstintingiy of\ntheir strength and of their effort.\nThey have the right to expect\nthat the same consideration will\nbe shown to them in then hour\nof need that they showed to the\ngovernment in its. It would in\ndeed ke a negation of the very\nprinciples for which this peo\nple's war was fought\u2014voiced\ntime and time again by leaders\ncf your administration and your\npredecessor\u2014if those to whom\nthe victory belongs should be\ncome casualties of the peace,\nMass unemployment for workers\nis not good for. the nation, either.\nSuch a terrific slash in purchasing\npower will create a deflationary\nthat will 3ucic down with it all\nlor an economy of con\nstantiy Production and\nemployment\nOfficial govemmeE -3 urcct, f\ndiet unemployment for w*'' miihon\nworkers If that number of w. T ers\nshould be unemployed for an entu*.\nyear, more than r I 3 b.i\u2019icn would be\ns\u2019ashed f r cm the nat on s purchasing\npower. That cannc be allowed to\nhappen, Mr. President, unless the\nAdministration is prepared to as\nsume the responsibility for the chaos\nthat will follow\nPROPOSAL\nin your recent message to